Cape Town - Health Minister Aaron Motsoaledi has confirmed that there is an outbreak of food-borne disease Listeriosis in South Africa. “In October 2017 the Multisectional National Outbreak response team was briefed on the situation in the country. Tracing from the 1st of January 2017, as of 29 November a total of 557 laboratory confirmed listeriosis cases have been reported from all provinces,” Motsoaledi said. Gauteng had the most number of reported cases at 62%, with the Western Cape registering 13%. Listeriosis is a type of food poisoning caused by eating foods contaminated with the bacteria listeria monocytogenes. The bacteria are widely found in nature and can be found in soil, water and vegetation. A listeria infection may result in flu-like symptoms with diarrhoea, infection of the blood stream and infection of the brain. Motsoaledi said the disease can be treated with antibiotics. Those who are more at risk contracting the disease are newborns, the elderly, pregnant women and people with a weak immune systems. There have been 36 deaths reported in South Africa so far. Motsoaledi said it was still unknown where the outbreak originated. “There are four possible sources; farms, food processing plants, retail and food preparation at home. The source of this outbreak is currently being investigated,” he said.  marvin.charles@inl.co.za  Cape Argus